The Vaal dam supplies water to 33% of the population. As of November the 4th, the dam levels were filled at 46.2% of full capacity; as of November the 11th, the dam is only 44.5% filled - a significant reduction to the previous month. September/October of 2019 also saw a 33% drop in capacity compared to last year during the same months. There was also a record low rainfall during the pre-winter season (October to March) where rainfalls are expected to fill the dams; 485.7mm in 2019 compared to 645.8mm in 2018. This lack of rainfall phenomenon coupled with consumption, has put water supply in question.  Lindiwe Sisulu, Minister of Human Settlement, Water and Sanitation, has reassured that no “water-shedding” will occur. Has the government learnt from the Cape Town water crisis in 2017?  EXPLORE Data Science cohort of 2019 looked at some of the factors influential to Cape Town’s water crisis. SQL, Python and PowerBI dashboards were just some industry leading tools used to do the analysis and create beautiful presentations.
